3. Time-Barred Debt
A debt becomes time-barred if it is not claimed for a period of three years
from the date it becomes due. Where there is an agreement, made in writing and
signed by the debtor to pay wholly or in part a time-barred debt, the agreement is
valid even though it is not supported by any consideration. Such an agreement is
valid if the following conditions are fulfilled. (Sec. 25(3))
a. The debt must be time-barred.
b. The promisor himself must be liable for the debt.
c. There must be an express promise to pay a time-barred debt.
d. The promise must be in writing and signed by the debtor or his agent.
