According to the English Common Law, a common carrier is liable as an
insurer of the goods. He is liable for damages to the goods whether he is
negligent or not. He is not responsible under the following circumstances:
a. Act of God
The Common carrier is not liable for losses due to an act of God. Usually
the lost caused by lightening, earthquake, flood etc. are due to an act of God.
b. Enemies of State
The carrier is not liable for losses caused by enemies of the state. The
enemies of the state mean alien enemies at war with Pakistan. It does not
include losses due to thieves, strike etc.
c. Inherent Defect
The common carrier is not liable for losses arising from inherent defects
e.g. evaporation of liquid material, perishing of fruits and vegetables, disease in
animals.
